      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are looking for the \"skeleton\" of the house, which is usually made of heavy timber or steel beams, not just the drywall or studs. If you see a thick, dark beam running horizontally or vertically through the attic or basement, that is almost certainly the main support system. If you see a thin, white wooden stud or a metal stud, that is likely just a non-load-bearing partition.\n\n**However, here is the most important thing to know:** You cannot see the main support system just by looking at the attic or basement. The main support system is often hidden *inside* the wall you are trying to rip out.\n\nIf you are looking at the wall itself, you should look for a **steel beam** (often called a \"beam\" or \"girder\") running through the center of the wall. If you see a steel beam, that is the main support. If you see a wooden beam, that is also the main support. If you see **nothing** but just drywall and studs, then the wall is likely not load-bearing.\n\nBut wait, you might be thinking of a \"load-bearing wall\" if you are thinking of a \"load-bearing\" wall. If you are thinking",
